      <section xml:id="sec-logic-laws">
        <title>Laws of Logic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            You may have noticed some common patterns running through some of the exercises by now.  Let's examine those patterns in more detail.
          </p>
          <p>
            First, let us look at the connections between the two sets of symbols we've used so far.
            <tabular halign="center" top="medium" left="medium">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Logic
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand q</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor q</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\notp</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>F</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>T</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Boolean Algebra
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>AB</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+B</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\nota</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </p>
          <p>
            In each case, we have symbols for negation, <em>or</em>, and <em>and</em>.  There are also equivalences with False/True for logic and 0/1 (or off/on) for Boolean algebra and logic circuits.  Let's see what else they have in common.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-identity-laws">
          <title>Identity Laws</title>
          <p>
            Consider the following truth table for the logical symbols.
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" left="medium">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>1</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand 0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor 0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand 1</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor 1</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </p>
          <p>
            You can replace the logic symbols in this table with the corresponding Boolean algebra notation.  From this, we can deduce the following <term>identity laws</term>:
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-identity-laws">
              <title>Identity Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="20%" margins="20%">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Logic</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>p\myand 0 \amp\Leftrightarrow 0</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myor 0\amp\Leftrightarrow p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myand 1\amp\Leftrightarrow p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myor 1\amp\Leftrightarrow 1</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Boolean</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>A\cdot 0\amp = 0</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+0\amp = A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A\cdot 1\amp = A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+1\amp = 1</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>

              </p>
            </assemblage>
            It is interesting to note that the first three Boolean identity laws look like laws of normal arithmetic with numbers.  The fourth law <em>does not</em> resemble any arithmetic law.  This is a clue that Boolean algebra is <em>not</em> equivalent to the algebra associated with the real numbers.
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-idempotent-laws">
          <title>Idempotent Laws</title>
          <p>
            We deduce the <term>idempotent laws</term> in the same way.  Consider the following table, given using logic notation:
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" left="medium">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  <m>p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor p</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            Boolean algebra notation could have been used in this table, instead.
          </p>
          <p>
            From this we can deduce the following:
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-idempotent-laws">
              <title>Idempotent Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="20%" margins="20%">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Logic</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>p\myand p \amp\Leftrightarrow p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myor p\amp\Leftrightarrow p</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Boolean</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>A\cdot A\amp = A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+A\amp = A</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-complement-laws">
          <title>Complement Laws</title>
          <p>
            Similarly, truth tables can be used to deduce the <term>complement laws</term>:
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-complement-laws">
              <title>Complement Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="20%" margins="20%">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Logic</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>\mynot(\notp) \amp\Leftrightarrow p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\,\myand\,\notp\amp\Leftrightarrow 0</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\,\myor\,\notp\amp\Leftrightarrow 1</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Boolean</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>\mybnot{\nota}\amp =A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A\cdot\nota\amp = 0</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+\nota\amp = 1</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-commutative-laws">
          <title>Commutative Laws</title>
          <p>
            The <term>commutative laws</term> state that the ordering of symbols is not significant for the logic operations <em>and</em> and <em>or</em>, and also for the corresponding operations in Boolean algebra.  The commutative law does not apply to all operations.  More on that later.
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-commutative-laws">
              <title>Commutative Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="20%" margins="20%">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Logic</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>p\myand q \amp\Leftrightarrow q\myand p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p \myor q\amp\Leftrightarrow q\myor p</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Boolean</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>A\cdot B\amp =B\cdot A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+B\amp =B+A</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-associative-laws">
          <title>Associative Laws</title>
          <p>
            <xref ref="exer-logic-commutative"/> illustrates the <term>associative law</term> for <em>or</em>.  You could construct a similar truth table for <em>and</em>.  The associative laws in Boolean algebra form look just like the associative laws of multiplication and addition of real numbers.  Remember, though, that Boolean algebra is not the same as the algebra of real numbers!
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-associative-laws">
              <title>Associative Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="30%" margins="auto">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Logic</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>(p\myand q)\myand r \amp\Leftrightarrow p\myand(q\myand r)</mrow>
                          <mrow>(p\myor q)\myor r\amp\Leftrightarrow p\myor(q\myor r)</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <term>Boolean</term>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>(A\cdot B)\cdot C\amp = A\cdot(B\cdot C)</mrow>
                          <mrow>(A+B)+C\amp =A+(B+C)</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-basic-logic-laws">
          <title>Summary So Far</title>
          <p>
            Here are all the laws identified so far, collected into one table for easy reference.  In the next subsection, we will examine how these laws are used to simplify logical/Boolean expressions <em>without</em> having to resort to constructing truth tables.
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" left="medium">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Law
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  Logic
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  Boolean Algebra
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Identity
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand 1\Leftrightarrow p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A\cdot 1=A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor 1\Leftrightarrow 1</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+1=1</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand 0\Leftrightarrow 0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A\cdot 0=0</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor 0\Leftrightarrow p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+0=A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Idempotent
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand p\Leftrightarrow p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A\cdot A=A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor p\Leftrightarrow p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+A=A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Complement
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mynot(\notp)\Leftrightarrow p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mybnot{\nota}=A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\,\myand\,\notp\Leftrightarrow 0 </m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A\cdot\nota=0</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\,\myor\,\notp\Leftrightarrow 1</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+\nota=1</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Commutative
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand q\Leftrightarrow q\myand p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A\cdot B=B\cdot A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor q\Leftrightarrow q\myor p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+B=B+A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Associative
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>(p\myand q)\myand r\Leftrightarrow p\myand(q\myand r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>(A\cdot B)\cdot C=A\cdot(B\cdot C)</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>(p\myor q)\myor r\Leftrightarrow p\myor(q\myor r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>(A+B)+C=A+(B+C)</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-simplifying-logical-expr1">
          <title>Simplifying Logical Expressions</title>
          <p>
            We use the laws of logic to simplify logical expressions or to prove logical equivalence without resorting to truth tables.
          </p>
          <p>
            Suppose we wish to simplify <m>(p\myand q)\myor(\notq\,\myand\, 0)\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)</m>.  Note that this would require a truth table with 8 rows to show all combinations of <m>p</m>, <m>q</m>, and <m>r</m>.  Less work is required to simplify the expression using the laws of logic.  You can think of the laws of logic as summary statements of truth tables.
          </p>
          <p>
            The procedure for simplifying an expression using the laws of logic is to simplify each piece of the expression using a single law, then write the name of the law you are using to one side. Writing the name of the law is <term>required</term>, and <term>not optional</term>!  If you are using more than one law, then use a separate line for each law/step.
          </p>
          <p>
            Let's use the laws of logic to simplify the statement given earlier:
            <tabular halign="center">
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>(p\myand 1)\myor(\notq\,\myand\, 0)\myor(\notr\,\myand r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor 0\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  identity
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>(p\myor 0)\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  associative
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  identity
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor(r\,\myand\,\notr)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  commutative
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor 0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  complement
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  identity
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            So we see that <m>(p\myand q)\myor(\notq\,\myand\, 0)\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)\Leftrightarrow p</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The simplification can be done another way:
            <tabular halign="center">
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>(p\myand 1)\myor(\notq\,\myand \,0)\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor 0\myor(\notr\,\myand\,r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  identity
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor 0\myor 0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  complement
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p\myor 0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  definition of <em>or</em>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  identity
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            The conclusion is the same, as we should expect!
          </p>
          <example xml:id="examp-simpl-logic-laws">
            <statement>
              Simplify <m>(p\,\myor\,\notp)\myand(\notp\,\myor\,\notp)</m>.
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>(p\,\myor\notp)\myand(\notp\,\myor\notp)</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>1\myand(\notp\,\myor\,\notp)</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    complement
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>1\myand(\notp)</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    idempotent
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>\notp</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    identity
                  </cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
              (If you applied the laws correctly but in a different order or combination, you should still come to the same, correct conclusion.)
            </answer>
          </example>
        </subsection>
        <exercises xml:id="exers-sec-logic-laws">
          <exercise>
            <statement>
              Which of the following statements is always true?
              <ol>
                <li><m>\ </m>Darth Vader is both evil and not evil.</li>
                <li><m>\ </m>Darth Vader is both evil and evil.</li>
                <li><m>\ </m>Darth Vader is either evil or evil.</li>
                <li><m>\ </m>Darth Vader is either evil or not evil.</li>
              </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              Statement (d) is true because <m>p\,\myor \notp\Leftrightarrow 1</m>.  Note that you must assess each statement based on its logical structure, and not on the truth value of the instance.
            </solution>
          </exercise>
          <exercise>
            <statement>
              Which of the following statements is always false?
              <ol>
                <li><m>\ </m>The roadrunner has escaped from the wily coyote and he has not escaped from the wily coyote.</li>
                <li><m>\ </m>The roadrunner has escaped from the wily coyote and he has escaped from the wily coyote.</li>
                <li><m>\ </m>The roadrunner has escaped from the wily coyote or he has not escaped from the wily coyote.</li>
                <li><m>\ </m>The roadrunner has escaped from the wily coyote or he has escaped from the wily coyote.</li>
              </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              Statement (a) is, symbolically, <m>p\,\myand\,\notp</m>, which is logically equivalent to 0. So statement (a) is false regardless of whether roadrunner has or has not escaped from the wily coyote.
            </solution>
          </exercise>
