        <subsection xml:id="ssec-demorgan-and-contrapos">
          <title>
            De Morgan's Law and the contrapositive
          </title>
          <p>
            Consider the conditional <m>(p \myand{} q \myimplies{} r</m>.  The contrapositive would be <m>\mylnot{r} \myimplies{} \mylnot{(p \myand{} q)}</m>.  Applying De Morgan's Law gives <m>\mylnot{r} \myimplies{} (\mylnot{p} \myor{} \mylnot{q})</m>.  Notice the change from the <em>and</em> in the conditional to the <em>or</em> in the modified contrapositive.  Forgetting to make that change is an easy trap to fall into.
            <example xml:id="exmpl-demorgan-contrap1">
              <statement>
                Consider the conditional <q>If Jason sleeps in or gets caught in traffic, he will be late for class.</q>  What is the contrapositive?  Use De Morgan's Law to find your answer.
              </statement>
              <answer>
                The conditional here is
                <me>
                  (\text{sleep or traffic})\myimplies\text{ late}
                </me>
                The contrapositive is then

                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \mynot{\text{late}} \amp \myimplies \mynot{\text{sleep or traffic}}
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp \mynot{\text{sleep}}\text{ and }\mynot{\text{traffic}}
                  </mrow>
                </md>
                Therefore, the contrapositive is <q>If Jason is not late for class, then he didn't sleep in <em>and</em> he didn't get caught in traffic.</q>  The <em>or</em> changes into <em>and</em>, as indicated by De Morgan's Law.
              </answer>
            </example>
          </p>
        </subsection>
